834
00:35:51,000 --> 00:35:52,000
on this complex plane.

835
00:35:52,000 --> 00:35:53,000
Get used to that idea.

836
00:35:53,000 --> 00:35:55,000
Fields don't just have to be numbers.

837
00:35:55,000 --> 00:35:56,000
They can be complex numbers.

838
00:35:56,000 --> 00:35:58,000
They can be multi-component objects.

839
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:00,000
Yeah.

840
00:36:00,000 --> 00:36:02,000
Question.

841
00:36:02,000 --> 00:36:06,000
In the sombrero picture there,

842
00:36:06,000 --> 00:36:09,000
going in the mass fold direction,

843
00:36:09,000 --> 00:36:11,000
if you give it a big enough displacement,

844
00:36:11,000 --> 00:36:14,000
it'll go into the other equilibrium point.

845
00:36:14,000 --> 00:36:15,000
What does that mean in terms of...

846
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:16,000
Yeah.

847
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:17,000
If you give it a hard enough kick,

848
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:18,000
it'll go all the way up.

849
00:36:18,000 --> 00:36:19,000
It'll swing around.

850
00:36:19,000 --> 00:36:23,000
Does that manifest itself in some kind of particle?

851
00:36:23,000 --> 00:36:25,000
Well, the problem is that the amount of energy

852
00:36:25,000 --> 00:36:27,000
that would be involved for the Higgs field

853
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:32,000
is way beyond the energy

854
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:37,000
that even a big accelerator can...

855
00:36:37,000 --> 00:36:41,000
So it's out of the ballpark from even the LHC.

856
00:36:41,000 --> 00:36:42,000
But yes, I mean, in principle,

857
00:36:42,000 --> 00:36:45,000
you could give the field a big enough knock

858
00:36:45,000 --> 00:36:46,000
to knock it over the top.

859
00:36:46,000 --> 00:36:48,000
Not everywhere simultaneously in space.

860
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:50,000
That would be an enormous amount of energy,

861
00:36:50,000 --> 00:36:51,000
but in some region, yeah.

862
00:36:51,000 --> 00:36:53,000
But if that's exactly in

863
00:36:53,000 --> 00:36:55,000
line with the peak of the...

864
00:36:55,000 --> 00:36:56,000
Very unlikely.

865
00:36:56,000 --> 00:36:58,000
It would go off and wind up all over.

866
00:36:58,000 --> 00:36:59,000
Right.

867
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:00,000
So it's very unlikely.

868
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:01,000
Right.

869
00:37:01,000 --> 00:37:02,000
That's right.

870
00:37:02,000 --> 00:37:05,000
Yeah, it would make a monstrous splash of some kind

871
00:37:05,000 --> 00:37:07,000
going off and on.

872
00:37:07,000 --> 00:37:09,000
Let's take a 10-minute break.

873
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:10,000
Okay.

874
00:37:10,000 --> 00:37:13,000
Let's go through again...

875
00:37:13,000 --> 00:37:14,000
Yeah.

876
00:37:14,000 --> 00:37:17,000
...what we mean by a

877
00:37:17,000 --> 00:37:20,000
field as a function of space

878
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:23,500
and what this idea of a

879
00:37:23,500 --> 00:37:27,000
field which is a complex variable is.

880
00:37:27,000 --> 00:37:29,000
Just to make it clear once more.

881
00:37:29,000 --> 00:37:32,000
We have space, x, y, and z, right?

882
00:37:32,000 --> 00:37:34,000
Now we can have fields in space.

883
00:37:34,000 --> 00:37:36,000
Let's say scalar fields.

884
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:40,000
You can have a scalar field in space which...

885
00:37:40,000 --> 00:37:43,000
Now what characterizes it as being a scalar?

886
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:46,000
It means it doesn't change when you rotate coordinates.

887
00:37:46,000 --> 00:37:47,000
That's all it means.

888
00:37:47,000 --> 00:37:48,000
It doesn't change...

889
00:37:48,000 --> 00:37:49,500
Not when you rotate the

890
00:37:49,500 --> 00:37:51,000
coordinates we're talking about here.

891
00:37:51,000 --> 00:37:54,000
When you rotate the coordinates of real space,

892
00:37:54,000 --> 00:37:56,000
it doesn't change.

893
00:37:56,000 --> 00:37:58,000
That's what a scalar field is.

894
00:37:58,000 --> 00:38:00,000
Now you can have several scalar fields.

895
00:38:00,000 --> 00:38:03,000
Let's say in particular you can have two scalar fields.

896
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:05,000
Let's give them names.

897
00:38:05,000 --> 00:38:09,000
Let's call them phi i and phi r.

898
00:38:09,000 --> 00:38:12,000
They're two scalar fields.

899
00:38:12,000 --> 00:38:17,000
You can then assemble them if you like.

900
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:20,000
This is totally a matter of convention.

901
00:38:20,000 --> 00:38:22,000
It's totally a choice.

902
00:38:22,000 --> 00:38:23,000
It's a useful choice.

903
00:38:23,000 --> 00:38:26,500
It's one of these things in mathematics

904
00:38:26,500 --> 00:38:30,000
which sometimes are really just useful conventions.

905
00:38:30,000 --> 00:38:32,000
And this is one of them.

906
00:38:32,000 --> 00:38:33,500
In fact, the whole idea of

907
00:38:33,500 --> 00:38:35,000
complex numbers is a useful convention.

908
00:38:35,000 --> 00:38:38,000
It's a useful convention for representing pairs of numbers.

909
00:38:38,000 --> 00:38:40,000
That's all.

910
00:38:40,000 --> 00:38:42,000
And the pairs of numbers are called the real numbers.

911
00:38:42,000 --> 00:38:45,000
They're real and imaginary parts of the numbers.

912
00:38:45,000 --> 00:38:46,000
X...

913
00:38:46,000 --> 00:38:47,000
Not...

914
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:48,000
Better not call them X.

915
00:38:48,000 --> 00:38:49,000
X stands for space.

916
00:38:49,000 --> 00:38:50,000
Okay?

917
00:38:50,000 --> 00:38:55,000
But just real and imaginary components are just

918
00:38:55,000 --> 00:39:00,000
ways of speaking about pairs of real numbers.

919
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:01,500
Now it is a little

920
00:39:01,500 --> 00:39:03,000
more than pairs of real numbers.

921
00:39:03,000 --> 00:39:07,000
There's more structure that goes into the complex numbers.

922
00:39:07,000 --> 00:39:09,500
But, you know, fundamentally it's a

923
00:39:09,500 --> 00:39:12,000
way of talking about pairs of numbers.

924
00:39:12,000 --> 00:39:17,000
You can plot pairs of numbers on the Cartesian plane.

925
00:39:17,000 --> 00:39:19,000
The Cartesian plane is not real space.

926
00:39:19,000 --> 00:39:23,000
It's just the Cartesian plane in which you've

927
00:39:23,000 --> 00:39:27,000
plotted the real and imaginary parts of complex numbers.

928
00:39:27,000 --> 00:39:30,500
If I had two fields, two scalar fields, one

929
00:39:30,500 --> 00:39:34,000
of which I called phi real and the other...

930
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:35,000
That's its name.

931
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:37,000
Phi real and phi imaginary.

932
00:39:37,000 --> 00:39:40,000
I can assemble them together into a complex field.

933
00:39:40,000 --> 00:39:41,000
Okay?

934
00:39:42,000 --> 00:39:44,000
Yeah.

935
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:46,000
A complex field.

936
00:39:46,000 --> 00:39:49,500
And at each point of space, there would

937
00:39:49,500 --> 00:39:53,000
be a phi real and a phi imaginary.

938
00:39:53,000 --> 00:39:54,000
Okay?

939
00:39:54,000 --> 00:39:57,500
At each point of space, I could go and

940
00:39:57,500 --> 00:40:01,000
plot the value of the field on the complex plane.

941
00:40:01,000 --> 00:40:04,000
Keep in mind, the complex plane is not space.

942
00:40:04,000 --> 00:40:07,000
It's just an auxiliary construction.

943
00:40:07,000 --> 00:40:09,500
An auxiliary construction which is

944
00:40:09,500 --> 00:40:12,000
useful in replacing two real fields

945
00:40:12,000 --> 00:40:15,000
by one complex symbol.

946
00:40:15,000 --> 00:40:16,000
That's all it is.

947
00:40:16,000 --> 00:40:18,000
It's a trick for representing...

948
00:40:18,000 --> 00:40:23,000
for cutting down the number of equations that you write.

949
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:25,500
Cutting it in half, basically, by

950
00:40:25,500 --> 00:40:28,000
writing them as equations for complex variables.

951
00:40:28,000 --> 00:40:30,000
Okay?

952
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:32,000
So, in that language, you

953
00:40:32,000 --> 00:40:34,000
would say that the scalar field...

954
00:40:34,000 --> 00:40:39,000
the complex scalar field phi is that... just that.

955
00:40:39,000 --> 00:40:41,000
It's a complex scalar field.

956
00:40:41,000 --> 00:40:43,500
And at every point in space,

957
00:40:43,500 --> 00:40:46,000
real space, it has a value.

958
00:40:46,000 --> 00:40:48,000
That value is not a single number.

959
00:40:48,000 --> 00:40:50,000
It's a pair of numbers.

960
00:40:50,000 --> 00:40:51,000
Why?

961
00:40:51,000 --> 00:40:53,000
Because it's a pair of fields to begin with.

962
00:40:53,000 --> 00:40:55,000
That pair of numbers can be plotted.

963
00:40:55,000 --> 00:40:56,500
So, at this point of space

964
00:40:56,500 --> 00:40:58,000
over here, the field is over here.

965
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:01,000
At that point of space, the field is over here.

966
00:41:01,000 --> 00:41:02,000
At that point, it's over here.

967
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:04,000
And so forth.

968
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:08,000
That's the idea of a complex scalar field.

969
00:41:08,000 --> 00:41:11,000
Sometimes, the real and imaginary parts of a complex field

970
00:41:11,000 --> 00:41:14,000
are called the real and imaginary components of the field.

971
00:41:14,000 --> 00:41:16,000
But don't get those confused with

972
00:41:16,000 --> 00:41:18,000
the components of a vector field

973
00:41:18,000 --> 00:41:20,500
or a tensor field or

974
00:41:20,500 --> 00:41:23,000
the components of the gravitational field.

975
00:41:23,000 --> 00:41:25,500
Those components have to do

976
00:41:25,500 --> 00:41:28,000
with projections onto real space-time coordinates.

977
00:41:28,000 --> 00:41:31,000
This has to do with the

978
00:41:31,000 --> 00:41:34,000
projections onto this fictitious two-dimensional plane

979
00:41:34,000 --> 00:41:38,000
that's useful for writing pairs of numbers.

980
00:41:38,000 --> 00:41:41,000
Now, once you realize that you can write...

981
00:41:41,000 --> 00:41:44,000
the field as a complex variable

982
00:41:44,000 --> 00:41:47,000
and plot it on the two-dimensional plane like that,

983
00:41:47,000 --> 00:41:51,000
then it becomes a possible symmetry of nature

984
00:41:51,000 --> 00:41:54,000
or a possible symmetry of mathematics

985
00:41:54,000 --> 00:41:56,000
to rotate the field.

986
00:41:56,000 --> 00:41:58,000
In other words, there might be a

987
00:41:58,000 --> 00:42:00,000
symmetry which says that you can relabel

988
00:42:00,000 --> 00:42:05,000
or redefine phi i and phi r by rotation.

989
00:42:05,000 --> 00:42:08,000
And that happens when...

990
00:42:08,000 --> 00:42:11,000
when we have Lagrangians like this,

991
00:42:11,000 --> 00:42:16,000
which don't change when you do what?

992
00:42:16,000 --> 00:42:18,000
When you multiply phi by e

993
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:20,000
to the i times a phase.

994
00:42:20,000 --> 00:42:22,000
These are the class of Lagrangians

995
00:42:22,000 --> 00:42:25,500
which don't change when you rotate

996
00:42:25,500 --> 00:42:29,000
the field simultaneously everywhere in space.

997
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:32,000
When you rotate it in this fictitious plane.

998
00:42:32,000 --> 00:42:33,500
In other words, take the

999
00:42:33,500 --> 00:42:35,000
field at every point of space

1000
00:42:35,000 --> 00:42:37,000
and you rotate its value.

1001
00:42:37,000 --> 00:42:39,000
You give a new value to the field,

1002
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:41,000
which is related to the old,

1003
00:42:41,000 --> 00:42:43,000
and you rotate it in this way,

1004
00:42:43,000 --> 00:42:45,000
changing the angle here,

1005
00:42:45,000 --> 00:42:47,000
rigidly everywhere in space,

1006
00:42:47,000 --> 00:42:50,000
then this Lagrangian does not change.

1007
00:42:50,000 --> 00:42:52,000
We went through that last time,

1008
00:42:52,000 --> 00:42:54,000
and that's the basic idea of

1009
00:42:54,000 --> 00:42:56,000
a complex field with a symmetry,

1010
00:42:56,000 --> 00:42:58,000
with a symmetry of...

1011
00:42:58,000 --> 00:43:00,000
called U1 symmetry.

1012
00:43:00,000 --> 00:43:02,000
It's a global symmetry.

1013
00:43:02,000 --> 00:43:04,000
That's called a global symmetry.

1014
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:06,000
A global symmetry is one where you're

1015
00:43:06,000 --> 00:43:08,000
not allowed to change the phase angle

1016
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:10,000
in space.

1017
00:43:10,000 --> 00:43:12,000
It's rotated everywhere.

1018
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:15,000
So you can see that symmetry just

1019
00:43:15,000 --> 00:43:18,000
by looking at what's a function of rho?

1020
00:43:18,000 --> 00:43:20,000
Yeah.

1021
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:21,000
Well, you can look at

1022
00:43:21,000 --> 00:43:22,000
it in a number of ways.

1023
00:43:22,000 --> 00:43:24,000
You can see that since this has

1024
00:43:24,000 --> 00:43:26,000
real squared plus imaginary squared things in it,

1025
00:43:26,000 --> 00:43:28,000
whenever a thing is a function of real squared plus...

1026
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:30,000
And the other term was...

1027
00:43:30,000 --> 00:43:31,000
This one?

1028
00:43:31,000 --> 00:43:33,000
And the other term was a Pythagorean zero.

1029
00:43:33,000 --> 00:43:34,000
Yeah.

1030
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:35,000
Right.

1031
00:43:35,000 --> 00:43:36,000
Right.

1032
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:37,000
So this is a function of rho also.

1033
00:43:37,000 --> 00:43:39,000
You can see it here.

1034
00:43:39,000 --> 00:43:41,000
And incidentally, what does the symmetry

1035
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:43,000
operation do on rho and alpha?

1036
00:43:43,000 --> 00:43:46,000
Rho stays the same.

1037
00:43:46,000 --> 00:43:47,000
Rho stays the same.

1038
00:43:47,000 --> 00:43:48,000
And alpha?

1039
00:43:48,000 --> 00:43:50,000
It's not the same.

1040
00:43:50,000 --> 00:43:52,000
You shift it by a constant, namely

1041
00:43:52,000 --> 00:43:54,000
the angle that you're rotating the field by.

1042
00:43:54,000 --> 00:43:56,000
Well, shifting alpha by a

1043
00:43:56,000 --> 00:43:58,000
constant doesn't change its derivatives.

1044
00:43:58,000 --> 00:44:00,000
Yeah, that's why I was saying that the potential

1045
00:44:00,000 --> 00:44:02,000
is the only part where the derivative doesn't come in.

1046
00:44:02,000 --> 00:44:04,000
That's correct.

1047
00:44:04,000 --> 00:44:05,000
Right.

1048
00:44:05,000 --> 00:44:07,000
So...

1049
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:08,000
All right.

1050
00:44:08,000 --> 00:44:10,000
So I think we have the basic idea.

1051
00:44:10,000 --> 00:44:12,000
Now let's go through again...

1052
00:44:12,000 --> 00:44:13,000
All right.

1053
00:44:13,000 --> 00:44:14,000
Now, yes.

1054
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:18,000
Let's go through the idea of a gauge transformation.

1055
00:44:18,000 --> 00:44:19,500
We went through it last time,

1056
00:44:19,500 --> 00:44:21,000
so I'm just going to remind you.

1057
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:22,000
We're not going to spend

1058
00:44:22,000 --> 00:44:23,000
a lot of time on it.

1059
00:44:23,000 --> 00:44:25,500
We're going to do it as fast

1060
00:44:25,500 --> 00:44:28,000
as we can, but please ask questions.

1061
00:44:28,000 --> 00:44:31,000
It is not a symmetry of

1062
00:44:31,000 --> 00:44:34,000
this Lagrangian to multiply the field phi...

1063
00:44:38,000 --> 00:44:45,000
by an arbitrary function of position, by an arbitrary phase.

1064
00:44:45,000 --> 00:44:46,000
This is called a phase.

1065
00:44:46,000 --> 00:44:53,000
e to the i times this times phi of x.

1066
00:44:53,000 --> 00:44:58,000
This is not a symmetry.

1067
00:44:58,000 --> 00:45:00,000
We went through this last time.

1068
00:45:00,000 --> 00:45:03,000
We rewrote that Lagrangian in terms of phi prime

1069
00:45:03,000 --> 00:45:06,000
and found out that it didn't have the same form.

1070
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:12,500
In other words, the Lagrangian written up there, in particular,

1071
00:45:12,500 --> 00:45:19,000
the term derivative of phi star times the derivative of phi...

1072
00:45:19,000 --> 00:45:21,000
I don't have to put in the indices mu here.

1073
00:45:21,000 --> 00:45:22,000
You know about that.

1074
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:26,000
That is not the same as the derivative

1075
00:45:26,000 --> 00:45:30,000
of phi prime star derivative of phi prime.

1076
00:45:30,000 --> 00:45:31,000
Not the same.

1077
00:45:31,000 --> 00:45:34,000
And therefore, it is not a symmetry.

1078
00:45:34,000 --> 00:45:35,000
Okay?

1079
00:45:35,000 --> 00:45:36,000
This is not a symmetry.

1080
00:45:36,000 --> 00:45:37,000
Why?

1081
00:45:37,000 --> 00:45:40,000
That's because when the derivatives act, they act not

1082
00:45:40,000 --> 00:45:43,000
only on phi, but they act on theta here.

1083
00:45:43,000 --> 00:45:46,000
They act on theta if theta is variable.

1084
00:45:46,000 --> 00:45:48,500
If theta didn't vary in space,

1085
00:45:48,500 --> 00:45:51,000
then this would be a symmetry.

1086
00:45:51,000 --> 00:45:53,000
But if theta varies in space, it's not.

1087
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:57,000
We worked that out in detail last time, and

1088
00:45:57,000 --> 00:46:01,000
I'll show you in a moment what we found.

1089
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:03,000
But to make it a symmetry, you have

1090
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:05,000
to add another field, a kind of compensating field.

1091
00:46:05,000 --> 00:46:10,000
A compensating field that will compensate for the changes in

1092
00:46:10,000 --> 00:46:15,000
the Lagrangian when you shift the phase of the field.

1093
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:20,000
Keep in mind, it's useful to remember that shifting the

1094
00:46:20,000 --> 00:46:25,000
phase of the field is just adding a function to alpha.

1095
00:46:25,000 --> 00:46:26,000
Okay?

1096
00:46:26,000 --> 00:46:29,500
Shifting the phase of the field is

1097
00:46:29,500 --> 00:46:33,000
adding a function, theta of x, to alpha.

1098
00:46:33,000 --> 00:46:38,000
It changes the phase angle everywheres by amount theta.

1099
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:39,000
All right?

1100
00:46:39,000 --> 00:46:42,000
If theta is a constant, it's a symmetry.

1101
00:46:42,000 --> 00:46:44,000
If theta is not a constant, it's not a symmetry.

1102
00:46:44,000 --> 00:46:46,000
In order to make it a

1103
00:46:46,000 --> 00:46:48,000
symmetry, you have to add another field.

1104
00:46:48,000 --> 00:46:51,000
And the other field is called the vector potential.

1105
00:46:51,000 --> 00:46:53,000
